TY  - JOUR
AU  - Cong, Lin William
AU  - He, Zhiguo
AU  - Li, Jiasun
T1  - Decentralized Mining in Centralized Pools
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaa040
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 34
IS  - 3
SP  - 1191
EP  - 1235
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - The rise of centralized mining pools for risk sharing does not necessarily undermine the decentralization required for blockchains: because of miners’ cross-pool diversification and pool managers’ endogenous fee setting, larger pools better internalize their externality on global hash rates, charge higher fees, attract disproportionately fewer miners, and grow more slowly. Instead, mining pools as a financial innovation escalate miners’ arms race and significantly increase the energy consumption of proof-of-work-based blockchains. Empirical evidence from Bitcoin mining supports our model’s predictions. The economic insights inform other consensus protocols and the industrial organization of mainstream sectors with similar characteristics but ambiguous prior findings.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaa040
ER  - 



